ownedComment.body: This is the data model for the Simulation Database, a specification of the IVOA Theory Interest Group.
This profile defines the domain specific UML dialect for the IVOA data modelling efforts.

UML DataType is the base class of Primitive Type and Enumeration.
This types are generic and does not represent specific implementation types.
Primitive type is a predefined datatype which does not have a structure.
ivoaIdentifier is a DataType since it has possibly a structure.

This stereotype indicates that an atribute represents a term in a particular ontology.
To be @deprecated@ use skosconcept instead

MaxLength defines the maximum length for a string value (or the precision for a number).
If MaxLength is undefined, then the following rules apply : - String [30] - Number [Real 4 bytes] for floating point numbers - Number [Integer 4 bytes] for integer numbers
This guarantees that that value is unique in a collection so a couple (container_id, attribute) must be unique
This attribute must be unique in the SimDB Database (unique contraints)
Indicates that this field can be used to order a collection of parent class

This stereotype, when assigned to an attribute indicates that the atribute must have as value a concept in a particular SKOS vocabulary. The tag skosVocabularyURI MUST be used to indicate which vocabulary is used.
Any model element can be given this sterotype. It allows one to add some specific labels as tags to the element. For example UTYPE.

If the model element represents an element in another data model, that element can be indicated by adding its UTYPE as this tag's value. Note that we allow an element to have multiple UTYPEs (multiplicity = 0..*).

This is the main/root package of the SimDB data model. It contains the other packages, and also some classes that might be better imported from the resource model of the IVOA registry WG. However those types were deemed to be too restrictive for our purposes.
Anyway, our approach is that an instance of the SimDB datamodel can be used to generate registry rsources, for example using XSLT, but is does not have to contain resources.
This package holds on to SimDB experiments and their results.
This class represents the basic simulations from which eventually all SimDB data products are derived. It extends Experiment by adding descriptions of the physical processes that were simulated

Reference to the Simulator that was used to run this Simulation. Thie reference overrrides(subsets) the simlar reference from Experiment to Protocol, indicating that the type of the protocol reference must be a Simulator, not just any Protocol.
The date/time at which the simulation was completed

This collections associates this Simulation to the Simulator's physics that was actually used. This element represents the possibility in most simulator codes to turn on or off specific physical processes in a simulation run. Examples are the option to have a pure dark matter simulation in an SPH code. Or a hydro code without gravity. The collection of AppliedPhysics objects references thos modules that were actually used.
The simulator that was used in this simulation. This reference overrides the protocol reference of Experiment, indicating that not any protocol can be added as a reference, but only a Simulator

Represents statistics regarding the properties of the objects in the collection.
PREVIOUSLY This class represents the characterisation of a property of an object in a given object collection. It represents both a priori and a posteriori characterisations. With a priori characterisation we indicate possible and/or nominal [?] values the variable may take, it defines the possible range of values of the property. In contrast, an a posteriori characterisation of a property in an object collection provides summarising, likely statistical, information on the values that were actually taken up (observed, simulated) by the objects in the collection. The a priori characterisation is most similar, in fact a generalisation of the Characterisation model of the IVOA Data Model working group [3].
In the current model we stick to simple (numerical) quantities for characterising a collection of objects. For example the equivalent value of a support from [3] is absent, as it is not terribly useful for discovery and querying, even more so of course for concepts equivalent to sensitivity. [TBD How relevant is it for simulations? Examples if we require it for the actual meta data specification, for example for usages beyond query and discovery.]
TODO currently the characterisation is restricted to numericalobservables, generalisation comes later.
value of a property in a collection of objects
This attribute indicates which type if characterisation this object represents. I.e. it indicates how to interpret the value. For a complete understanding one also needs the aPriori attribute.

If 'true', this attribute indicates that the characterisation is aPriori. That is it indicates that the value says something about what the publisher believes are the possible values the characterised property can assume. An "p priori" characterisation is therefore a summary of the effects that the input configuration (parameters, input data, the "provenance-actual experiment" therefore) is EXPECTED to have on the final result (represented by the collections of representation objects and their properties).
Alternatively, if the value is "false", it indicates that the charecterisation is a posteriori, i.e. it says something about the actual values that were assumed. This requires in general some level of post processing beyond simply storing the result, but as in general the characterisation types are simple statistical quantities this need not modelled as a separate experiment.

The property of the object type that is being characterised. In the IVOA DM's characterisation model this is represented by specified objects, such as spatialaxis, timeaxis etc. Here we do not know in advance which kind of property is characterised, hence this explicit reference.

We assume that a single Snapshot can consist of collections of objects (ObjectType). For example some simulations can produce both dark matter, stellar and gas particles, together building up the whole target objects. Each of these sets of particles is in general separately characterised and the ObjectCollection class provides an anchor for this. They may also be separately stored
This collection contains the characterisations of the different properties that summarise the properties of the representation objects in this object collection.
Gives the number of objects in this collection
This reference indicates the type of object stored in this collection.

the characterisations of the different variables. In contrast to the domain model in [2] we make no distinction w.r.t. a priori and a posteriori characterisation as separate classes/collection, but load all possible characterising quantities in one

Base class of objects that can be described by, queried by, discovered by the SimDB protocol. It included simulations of spatial systems and their "level-1" derived data products.
The base class for those kinds of experiments that can produce representations of a part of the universe.
This collection represents the different kinds of objects that were being simulated. These objects represent the goal of the experiment.
The collection of snapshots that are the individual results as function of time of the simulation or other SimDB Experiment.
The protocol according to which this experiment was performed. Will in general be overridden by sub-classes of Experiment to indicate a sub-class of Protocol
Similar to TargetObject, the physical processes that are being investigated in this experiment.
The parameter settings that, together with possible input data sets and limtations on the calculated properties define this experiment and separate it from others run with the same protocol.
The collection of association objects giving indicating which Snapshot(s) of another experiment were used in this one, for example in post-processing.
The collection of actual representation object types that were used in this experiment.
Collection of associative AppliedAlgorithm objects

This class represents a part of the universe at a particular point in time, or possibly a more general sub-volume of space-time, for example a light-cone. We realise this does not represent all possible outputs of simulations. For example some simulations of dense (collisional) stellar systems produce orbits of the individual particles, at individual output times . In general though those results can be used to produce snapshots as well (Peter Teuben, private communication). Hence for the current version of the model we propose the use of Snapshot results of simulations and other experiments as well, the only exception being light-cones through cosmological simulations
We anticipate that many results contain objects of different types. For each of these types a separate collection of objects is provided on the snapshot

The time in the simulation at which this snapshot is produced. A real value in terms of the timestep units that are being used. [TBD need to find a place for those units, note that we need to support co-moving quantities !]

The typical size of the target system in this snapshot. Left up to the data publisher to give a useful value for this. Is not necessarily equal to the size of the box containing the full simulation (covered by Characterisation). Could be the rough size of the galaxy merger, or cluster, or the size of a box containing 90% of the mass or whatever
We anticipate that many results contain objects of different types. For each of these types a separate collection of objects is provided on the snapshot

Represents a Experiment that acts on a pre-existing Snapshot to produce another Snapshot. In standard terminology this produces Level 1 data products (this is true whether the original Snapshot was a Level 0 products or already a Level 1 product)

The experiment whose results are being post-processed by this PostProcessing step.
TBD This is a very simple(simplistic) view of post-processing, that the results of a single experiment are manipulated only.
The post-processing protocol according to which the post-processing experiment is performed. Overrides the protocol reference on Experiment.
Associates a snapshot to a Postprocessing experiment. The associated snapshot is assumed to have been the target of the post-processing
The snapshot of an other experiment that was used by the current one as input data.
Describes the role that the input data set plays in the experiment.
The protocol according to which this experiment was performed. Will in general be overridden by sub-classes of Experiment to indicate a sub-class of Protocol
The properties of the object. Ex: mass, position,velocity
The actual snapshot being post-processed

This class represents the fact that some simulations are run to investigate physical processes, rather than simulation specific objects or systems. Instances of this class can be used to describe this. For example one may study "turbulence", or "gravitational cluster" or "galaxy formation".
A term from the AstroJournalSubjectKeywords ontology.

To run an Experiments, one usually needs to assign values to parameters defined on the corresponding Protocol. This class makes the association between the Experiment and the parameters. TBD Parameters can have many different types and so the type of the value can in general not be pre-assigned. One might consider using Value as type, but for usability purposes we decided to sub class this class instead to deal with numeric and all other parameters. Alternatively one could use a string.
Reference to the actual input parameter whose value is being set.

The collection of simulator input parameters used in this simulation. These parameters must correspond to actual parameters that can be set on the simulator.
the parameters used in the experiment. In this logical model the parameters are both defined and given a value in a single object. In the analysis model parameters are defined on the protocol, and only given a value on the experiment
Many simulation codes allow one to turn on or off modules corresponding to different physics. This class is aan association betwene the Simulation and the Physics available on a certaion protocol.
Reference to the Simulator's Physcis module that is used in the experiment.
The collection of physical processes modelled in this simulation

This enumeration lists various statistics that can be calculated for the properties of collection of objects.
PREVIOUS This enumeration lists possible ways to characterise a collection of Property-s in a snapshot. The literals in this enumeration in general correspond to the result of a statistical operation on this collection (when a posteriori) or on the corresponding operation on the a priori probability distribtion (assuming this can be defined) of its values.
TBD May need to be turned into an ontology, i.e. the values are not defined in this model, but in an external set of reference data.
A typical value, as judged by the publisher of the snapshots. May not correspond to a predefined statistical operation such as mean or mode.
Represents the minimum ('possible' if a priori, 'attained' if a osteriori) value for the characterised property.
Represents the maximum ('possible' if a priori, 'attained' if a osteriori) value for the characterised property.
Represents the mean ('expected' if a priori, 'attained' if a posteriori) value for the characterised property.
Represents the expected/attained standard deviation for the characterised property.
This value indicates that a given object collection has a constant value for the property characterised by this value.

Protocols often allow one to choose which representation object types one wants to use in an experiment. For example, SPH codes may have dark matter particles, gass particles, star particles. A given experiment may not require all. This class associates the experiment to the actual representation object types that are used.
Reference to the RepresentationObjectType that is associated to the experiment by this association class.

Apart form allowing a user the freedom to choose between available representation object types, Protocols may also allow one to choose from available properties on the selected object.This collection embodies that choice for the selected experiment representation object.
Indicates the different object types used to represent the system that is being simulated/produced by the experiment
the type of used object

Apart form allowing a user the freedom to choose between available representation object types, Protocols may also allow one to choose from available properties on the selected object. This class represents such a choice.
Reference to the property that is being chosen by the ExperimentProperty object.

This class represents the actual system that is being simulated. Instances of this object should correspond to physical objects and/or systems. They should be the answer to queries such as, 'what does this simulation simulate?'
Indication on how many objects of this type are being modelled. [TBD This may become an enumerated value, like 'one, two, tens, many ...'].

If the target object type referes to a real object, this attribute allows one to indicate which object. This is performed by a URI that shold identify the object in the Ontology of SimbadIdentifiedNames
In some cases a real identified object in the universe is being modelled. If that is the case, this attribute allows that object to be identified. We assume a list of such objects may be provided through some means, embodied by the IdentifiedObject data type. Ex: Galaxy, Antennae, M31
TBD can this be seen as a SKOS concept ?

Ontology based label for this object. Hope is that the IVOA Semantics working group effort on an ontology for astronomical objects will be rich enough to provide the values for this attribute. Ex: star, large scale structure, galaxy, jet
maybe, a subject keyword from the astronomical journals list

The property of the object type that is being characterised. In the IVOA DM's characterisation model this is represented by specified objects, such as spatialaxis, timeaxis etc. Here we do not know in advance which kind of property is characterised, hence this explicit reference.

indication how this physical process is implemented in the simulator. If there is in general only one Algorithm required per Physics oject, we may consider putting the Algorithm.label attribute as an attribute on the Physics class and remove the Algorithm class. Ex: (gravity) tree-PM, (hydrodynamics) AMR

Represents the application of a particular algorithm in an experiment.
TODO decide whether we need this.
The actual algorithm that is applied

This project defines protocols for SimDB. These represent "ways in which to do a SimDB experiment". Examples are the various simulation and post-processing codes. Some of the concrete cases are merely here as place holder or xamples.
TODO we need to decide which ones are relevant and keep them. May need input from SimDAP effort.

This class represents physical processes that are taken into account by a simulation. These may correspond to equations of motion evolving the simulated system from one state to the next, but also specifications of parameters describing initial conditions belong her.
Name by which this physical process is referred to in the simulator code
Short description of the physical process represented by this class.
If applicable, a more formal, TeX form of the evolution equation(s) used to represent this physical process.

The name by which this process is (approximately) known in the IVOA ontology of physical processes. Ex: gravity, hydrodynamics, cosmology
The name by which this process is (approximately) known in the list of subject keywords of the Astrophysical Journal, MNRAS and A&A

This class represents the simulation software that is available to run a simulation. We do not prescribe this model in great detail here [TBD should we?]. We only add the collection of physical processes that are available.
TODO one might argue we need a separate collection of numerical algorithms that implement the physical processes.
Collection of physical processes that can be simulated using this simulator.

The base class of all protocols producing snapshots. These objects define how SimDB experiments can be performed, like a blue-print, template. For simulations the protocol will be the simulation code, here represented by Simulator. In the analysis model this class is more fully defined, but for the logical model for discovering SimDB experiments much of its components are moved to the Experiment itself

link where the code can be downloaded, if available
web page where documentation of this simulator can be obtained
the version of the simulator code that was used
Collection of parameter groups. This is a utility colection, indicating that a particular grouping of parameters is natural. Useful for browsing the protocol's contents.
The collection of representation objects available to represent the 3+1D universe in this protocol.
Collection of input parameters for this protocol.

This collection indicates which algorithms were applied in the experiment.
TODO should be put on Protocol with an association object taking its place under Experiment
This concrete subclass of Protocol represents protocols that deal with post-processing results of earlier experiments. We do not specify this much further in this version of the model.

Represents a (natural) grouping of input parameters. Especially in protocols with large numbers of parameters it may be useful to group these for browsing purposes for example. As browsing is likely an important mode of access to SimDB resources this possibility was introduced.
Short description of the purpose of this group.
Name given to this group.
Collection of associative member objects, indicating which parameter is part of the group.
Associative class, representing a selection of a parameter in a parameter grouping.
Reference to the selected input parameter.

This class represents the smallest units from which a target system/object is built. It defines also the actual objects that the Snapshot-s contain. Examples are the particles in an N-body simulation, the cells in an adaptive mesh simulations, the halos in the result of a group finder

Indicates the type of representation object according to the enumeration defined in this model.
TODO we need to decide whether we need this label to be an ontology term instead of getting values form an enumeraiton.
Name that this type of particle is given in an appropriate ontology (or dictionary, or standard vocabulary, or ...). For now we use the

Represents a standard name for the objects that can be used to represent a snapshot of the universe in SimDB data products. Examples from simulations are n-body particle, SPH particle, mesh cell. But also simplified representations of astronomical objects could be used here, for example in halo catalogues or semi-analytical galaxy catalogues, both results of post-processing experiments
NB This should be transferred to an appropriate external ontology!
Represents the case where point particles are used to represent the simulated world.
Represents the case where extended particles with hydro properties are used to represent the simulated world in an SPH simulation.
Represents the case whereextended particles are used to represent the simulated world.
Represents the case where simple, non-structured/subdivided mesh cells are used to represent the simulated world in a regular grid.
Represents the case where mesh cells taht may be hierarchically subdivided are used to represent the simulated world in an adaptive mesh refinemenet simulation.

Represents the case where mock astronomical objects with their "physical" properties are used to represent the simulated world. Mainly found in results of post-processing. Examples are dark matter halos as the result of a cluster finder, synthetic galaxies as the result of semi-analytical simulations or halo occupation distributions algorithms.
Represents the case wherecustom objects, for which there is no existing term available in this enumeration, are used to represent the simulated world.

This class represent a parameter setting for a SimDB experiment. The parameter can be used in describing the physics (for example mass of a particle), in the initial conditions (for example cosmology), in the numerical implementation (for example mesh size)
A label to be given to this input parameter.
Represents the numerical algorithm representing a physical process in the simulator code
The name given to this algorithm.
Short description of this algorithm.
Short name by which this implementation is known in the ontology of numerical implementations. Ex: n-body, tree, amr, ...

This is a thin copy of the Registry Resource model's Resource that borrowes some of its elements. It *is not* a Registry Resource though. In particular we want to refine the content model here. Using a restriction of the res:Resource leads to problems, as we'd like to extend the Resource at the same time. Hence we create a new type.

For Protocol : The name by which this simulator is commonly known. Ex: Gadget, Flash
For Project : the name of the project
For Experiment : the name of this experiment
A description of this resource.
a URL to the publication describing the experiment
The UTC date and time this resource metadata description was created.
The UTC date this resource metadata description was last updated.
a tag indicating whether this resource is believed to be still actively maintained.
The collection of contacts, parties that have played a role in the creation and/or publishing of this resource.
Information that can be used for contacting someone

the name or title of the contact person.
This can be a person's name, e.g. "John P. Jones" or a group, "Archive Support Team".

the contact mailing address
All components of the mailing address are given in one string, e.g. "3700 San Martin Drive, Baltimore, MD 21218 USA".
the contact email address

the contact telephone number
Complete international dialing codes should be given, e.g. "+1-410-338-1234".
The role this party plays in the Resource
This package holds on to classes that allow instances defining generic objects and object hierarchies.
An associative class representing a child object in a custom object hierarchy.
Reference to the ObjectType that is the type of the objectProperty.
Name of the variable representing the child object on the parent object.
The cardinality/multiplicity of the child object in the containing object.
Assocuiative object that represents a member in a property group.
Reference to the actual property this class associates to a property group.
This class represents a naturla grouping of properties on the object type. Is used for presentation purposes in a browsing environment.
Name of this paarameter grouping.
Collection of members of this parameter grouping.
Description of this group.
The properties of an object. Similar to the FIELD in a VOTable
the UCD of this property. [TBD Could be generalised to OntologyObject if necessary]
This class represents and abstract object type, and can thus be seen as a meta-modelling construct. It allows model instances that represent complex object definitions.
Collection of properties.
The name of this object type.
Short description of this object type.
Collection of associations to object types that are contained within this object or referenced by it.
Collection of property groups.
Represents a generic field like object.
the name of this parameter or property. Ex: omegaLambda, particleMass, linking length
the data type of this parameter or property
The cardinality of this parameter or property
Short description of this parameter or property
List of possible values : only defined when isEnumerated = true
indicates if this parameter or property only accept values coming from a list of valid values defined by the validValue collection
This represents a value for an enumerated parameter or property
the value as string : can be converted to the correct datatype of the asociated parameter or property
A description of this value.
Short name / alias for this value (useful in GUI)
Contains different roles a party can play in a resource.
Represents an owner of a resource.
Created the resource
Represents a publisher of a resource
A general contributor to the creation of the resource

This class represents a web service that can be used to access resources. The precise way this is done is not specified in detail. This may be more general than simply giving access to results of a single experiment. It may be a web service that can handle results of any experiment performed by a particular Protocol, or give access to all resources in a Project.
The web service is represented by a base URL and a service type. The type may be a standard to be developed by the SimDAP specification, or a simple custom service. In the latter case the base URL should point to a web page that presents further details.

The base URL of this web service. In case the web service has a special, SimDAP type, parameters may be added to this according to the relevant specification, to apply the web service directly to a given snapshot.
The type of web service. The possible values are currently defined by an enumeration. The literals there should be matched to the SimDAP specification.
Collection of resources that are made available in this web service.
The id by which this service is registered in an IVOA Resource Registry
Class representing an association between the containing WebService and the Resources that are being made accessible by it.
Indicates the Resource that the AccessibleResource class associates to the WebService
Description of how the resource is made available by the web service.

This enumeration indicates a list of possible service types that can be applied to snapshots of a given simulation. The contents of this enumeration will be decided evenatually by a SimDAP protocol specification, though 'custom' is always available and not specified in SimDAP.
Represents a service that allows one to download a snapshot.
Represents a SimDAP service that defines a cut-out operation on an existing snapshot.
Represents a SimDAP service that defines a (re)gridding operation on an existing snapshot. NB This may be have to be renamed depending on SimDAP standard.
Represents a SimDAP service that defines a cluster-finder operation on an existing snapshot, supposedly of an N-body simulation. NB This may be have to be renamed depending on SimDAP standard.
Represents a SimDAP service that defines a visualisation operation on an existing snapshot, producing a 2 dimensional grid. NB This may be have to be renamed depending on SimDAP standard.
Thie represents a general, unspecified online operation on a simulation. It may be of any kind, no restriction on interface.
A collection of SimDB experiments that have been executed together and are registered in an IVOA registry as a single Resource.
Collection of associatiions to the resources that make up this project.
Associative class between a Project and its constitutent SimDB/Resource-s.
Reference to another SimDB/Resource that is included in the containing project.
Describes the rolw of the referenced resource in this project.

The values of this type are to be used in the definition of metadata fields such as Property and InputParameter. These data types correspond to actual types used in computation and data representation and are slightly different from the more abstract types in the domain model in [2]. They are clearly related to similar concepts as in the DataType defined in the XML schema for VOTable.
A standard boolean type, with values 'true' and 'false', possibly represented differently in physical representations of the model.
A standard complex type. Here no limits on accuracy of constituent Re and Im parts.
Represents an exact time on an exact, given date.
A real*8 floating point datatype.
A real*4 floating point datatype.
An integer*4 integer datatype.
An integer*8 integer datatype.
A rational datatype, consisting of two integers representing the numerator and denominator.
an integer*2 integer datatype.
A standard string dattaype consisting of any type of character.
Possible values for cardinality attribute of a Property or a Parameter
Corresponds to 'Optional element'
Corresponds to 'Mandatory element'
Corresponds to 'Multiple but maybe Optional element'
Corresponds to 'Multiple with at least one element'
